observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The Officer in Charge of the Waterworks System must furnish the Municipal Accountant of the Monthly Billing, Reading, and Payment Monitoring Report for basis of the latter in recording the actual income earned and its corresponding receivable;
The Municipal Accountant, on periodic basis, must recognize the Impairment Loss – Loans and Receivables at an appropriate rate on the closed accounts/water service disconnection of consumers having unpaid water bills pursuant to IPSAS guidance that receivables must be presented at net realizable value during the reporting date;
The WWS concerned officers, together with the Municipal Treasury Office, must formulate effective collection strategy to intensify collections particularly on those overdue accounts;
Management must strictly enforce the disconnection policy as basis for impartial water service disconnection to consumers who were unable to pay the water bills after due date. Further, aforesaid policy must be incorporated in the Service Application for Water Connection duly signed by the applicant and notarized by a notarial officer;
As a matter of internal control, personnel from the Accounting Office by way of an Office Order issued by the Municipal Mayor, be assigned to randomly check the meter reading submitted to that office against the actual reading of consumers’ water meters.  Discrepancy noted or abnormal readings must be reported and investigated, copy furnish the Audit Team; and
The assets owned by the WWS such as waterworks facilities and the liabilities incurred in the construction/implementation of the LEE must be recorded in its books of accounts separate from other funds pursuant to the LEE Manual.
Management Comment:
Management noted the audit recommendations and ensured their compliance.

We reiterated our recommendations that:

The Municipal Accountant prepare and submit the BRS, together with the copies of the BS and supporting documents for the reconciling items, within the prescribed period for a timely review/verification of such report and prepare SLs per bank account;

The Municipal Treasurer prepare and update the Cash in Bank cashbooks for all accounts regularly; 

The Municipal Treasurer close the two bank accounts which are already dormant; and

The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer review, analyze and reconcile their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to determine the nature of each account and come up with the correct balances of the Cash in Bank accounts for all funds.

We recommended that:

The LGU, through the concerned offices/departments, observe the prudent fund management in its effort to curtail/eliminate/mitigate the spread of COVID-19 in the locality.  Henceforth, all PPAs related to COVID-19 must be judiciously planned according to priorities considering the scarce resources of the LGU and the urgent needs for health, safety, and livelihood of the constituents; 

Department/Units responsible for the procurement and distribution of food relief to account for all purchases, distribution, and balance and submit report immediately for further audit and verification and to avoid audit disallowance;

Submit properly accomplished Driver’s Trip Ticket, Monthly Summary Report of Official Travel, Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption for further audit and validation immediately upon receipt hereof, otherwise disbursement pertaining to aforesaid transaction shall be disallowed in audit for inability to adhere with the regulations; and

Observe and adhere to the required posting of APP, NOA, and PPAs implemented by the LGU to the GPPB portal for transparency and reportorial compliance.

We recommended that:

The LGU, strictly observe the laws and regulations on the budgeting and utilization of LDRRMF by utilizing the fund only for those allowed and legitimate PPAs to avoid depleting the fund for the expenditures outside the intent for its authorization; 

Explanation is requested as to why Section 4(u) of RA No. 11494, DBM LBC No. 124, and Item 3 of GPPB Resolution No. 18-2020 were not observed for the budgetary realignment of fund, procurements and disbursements, and the required posting to GPPB portal and other places; 

Submission of satisfactory explanation and additional documents, if warranted to justify the excessive price on the procurement of medical supplies and equipment, and the reports, accounting, and disposal of rice and diesel fuel otherwise aforesaid disbursement shall be suspended/disallowed in audit; and

Submit explanation on the excess disbursements from the amount appropriated from LDRRMF to COVID-19 related PPAs, otherwise the same shall be disallowed in audit for want of budgetary authorization from the Legislative.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) or its equivalent officers/employees to:

Strictly comply with the existing rules and regulations prescribing the guidelines in the formulation of Annual GPB, development of gender issues, GAD activities, and implementation and monitoring of the GPB.  Mainstreaming of regular PPAs must be made through the use of HGDG assessment tools to justify the attribution of the portion or whole costs to GAD budget; 

Avoid the general statements of the gender issue which do not necessarily reflect gender differences in the situation of women and men.  The gender issue must be specific and supported by evidence such as sex disaggregated data and gender analysis results;

Utilize the GAD Fund only for acceptable PPAs that would address the identified gender issues in the locality based on the RA No. 9710 or the  Magna Carta of Women, PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended, and other relevant international commitments; and

Submit a copy of the Annual GPB to COA within the prescribed period for the timely audit so that recommended corrective measures may also be issued in the appropriate time.

We recommended that:

Implement immediately and on timely basis the identified PPAs under the 20 per cent DF.  The Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer must monitor the implementation of the projects to fast tract its completion;

The members of the BAC schedule early all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave way for their timely implementation and completion; 

All 20 per cent DF projects must be effectively planned and the same shall be procurement-and implementation-ready within the fiscal year;

Satisfactory explanation is requested as why procurement law and regulations particularly GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 were not observed in the procurement of COVID-19 related PPAs and submit immediately the accounting of receipt and distribution of the procured food items for further validation in audit, otherwise disbursement related to said procurement shall be disallowed in audit; and

Submit FDA license of SAA Variety Store pertaining to the procurement of medical supplies purchased from that store.
